Load and Preprocess the Fashion MNIST Dataset¶

In [168]:
# Load and preprocess the Fashion MNIST dataset
(train_x, train_y), (test_x, test_y) = fashion_mnist.load_data()
train_x = train_x / 255
test_x = test_x / 255
train_x = train_x.reshape(-1, 784)
test_x = test_x.reshape(-1, 784)
train_x, val_x, train_y, val_y = train_test_split(train_x, train_y, test_size=0.2)

# Define the labels dictionary
labels = {0: "T-shirt/top", 1: "Trouser", 2: "Pullover", 3: "Dress", 4: "Coat",
          5: "Sandal", 6: "Shirt", 7: "Sneaker", 8: "Bag", 9: "Ankle boot"}

Define a Function to Plot Sample Images¶

In [169]:
# Define a function to plot sample images
def plot_sample(images, labels, title="Plot of sample images."):
    indexes = np.random.randint(0, len(images), size=10)
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(2, 5, sharex=True, sharey=True, figsize=(8, 4))
    axes = axes.flatten()

    for i, index in enumerate(indexes):
        axes[i].imshow(images[index].reshape(28, 28), cmap="gray")
        axes[i].set_title(f"{labels[labels[index]]}")
        axes[i].axis("off")
    fig.suptitle(title)
    plt.show()

# Call the plot_sample function for training data
plot_sample(train_x, train_y, "Plot of sample images for training data.")

# Check the shapes of train_x and test_x
print("Shape of train_x:", train_x.shape)
print("Shape of test_x:", test_x.shape)

Shape of train_x: (48000, 784)
Shape of test_x: (10000, 784)

Define the Models¶

In [170]:
# Define the models
models = []
histories = []
for i in range(3):
    model = ke.Sequential([
        Input(train_x.shape[1]),
        Dropout(0.2),
        BatchNormalization(),
        Dense(20, activation='relu'),
        Dense(13, activation='relu'),
        Dense(9, activation='relu'),
        Dense(10, activation='softmax')
    ])
    models.append(model)

Compile the Models¶

In [171]:
# Compile the models
opt = tf.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate=1e-4)
for model in models:
    model.compile(optimizer=opt,
                  loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                  metrics=['accuracy'])

Train the Models¶

In [172]:
# Train the models
for i, model in enumerate(models):
    print(f"Training model {i+1}")
    
    # Compile the model before training
    model.compile(optimizer='adam', loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy', metrics=['accuracy'])
    
    history = model.fit(
        x=train_x,
        y=train_y,
        epochs=300,  # Max epochs
        batch_size=700,
        validation_data=(val_x, val_y),
        callbacks=[EarlyStopping(patience=20, restore_best_weights=True)]  # Early stopping
    )
    histories.append(history)

for i, history in enumerate(histories):
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15, 5), dpi=300)  # Increase DPI for higher quality

    axs[0].set_xlabel("Epochs")

    axs[0].legend()
    axs[0].set_title(f"Model {i+1} - Loss")

    axs[1].plot(history.history["accuracy"], label="Training")
    axs[1].plot(history.history["val_accuracy"], label="Validation")
    axs[1].set_xlabel("Epochs")
    axs[1].set_ylabel("Accuracy")
    axs[1].legend()
    axs[1].set_title(f"Model {i+1} - Accuracy")

    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to prevent overlapping
    plt.show()

    # Print final loss values
    final_train_loss = history.history["loss"][-1]
    final_val_loss = history.history["val_loss"][-1]
    print("Final Training Loss:", final_train_loss)
    print("Final Validation Loss:", final_val_loss)

    # Print final accuracy values
    final_train_acc = history.history["accuracy"][-1]
    final_val_acc = history.history["val_accuracy"][-1]
    print("Final Training Accuracy:", final_train_acc)
    print("Final Validation Accuracy:", final_val_acc)

Identify the Best Set of Weights for Each Model to Avoid Overfitting¶

# Identify the best set of weights for each model to avoid overfitting
best_weights = []
best_val_losses = []

for i, history in enumerate(histories):
    print(f"Model {i+1} Training History:", history.history)
    if 'val_loss' in history.history and len(history.history['val_loss']) > 0:
        min_val_loss_epoch = np.argmin(history.history['val_loss'])
        best_val_losses.append(np.min(history.history['val_loss']))
        best_weights.append(history.model.get_weights())
    else:
        print(f"No validation loss recorded for Model {i+1}.")
        print(f"Training Loss: {history.history.get('loss')}")

# If no models had non-empty val_loss history, raise an error
if not best_weights:

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

# Loop through each model's history
for i, history in enumerate(histories, start=1):
    # Evaluate the model on the validation dataset
    val_predictions = models[i-1].predict(val_x)  # Using i-1 since models are indexed from 0
    val_predictions_classes = np.argmax(val_predictions, axis=1)
    
    # Calculate evaluation metrics for validation dataset
    accuracy = accuracy_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes)
    precision = precision_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes, average='weighted')
    recall = recall_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes, average='weighted')
    f1 = f1_score(val_y, val_predictions_classes, average='weighted')

    # Print evaluation metrics
    print(f"\nValidation Dataset Evaluation for Model {i}:")
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")
    print(f"Recall: {recall:.4f}")
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")

# Function for scoring ROC AUC score for multi-class
def multiclass_roc_auc_score(test_y, y_pred, average="macro"):
    test_y_encoded = np.zeros_like(y_pred)
    test_y_encoded[np.arange(len(test_y)), test_y] = 1
    auc_scores = []

    for idx, c_label in enumerate(labels):
        fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(test_y_encoded[:, idx], y_pred[:, idx])
        roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)
        auc_scores.append(roc_auc)
        print(f'AUC score for class {c_label}: {roc_auc:.4f}')
        plt.plot(fpr, tpr, label='%s (AUC:%0.2f)' % (c_label, roc_auc))
    
    avg_auc = roc_auc_score(test_y_encoded, y_pred, average=average)
    print(f'Average ROC AUC score: {avg_auc:.4f}')
    plt.plot(fpr, fpr, 'b-', label='Random Guessing')
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
    plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
    plt.title('ROC Curve')
    plt.show()
    return avg_auc
